Nafion enabled a well-dispersed suspension of GQDs-Cu, allowing a uniform coating of the surface of the Au electrode, also providing mechanical stability to the modifier. Without the use of Nafion, leaching of the modifying material from the electrode surface occurs. Thus mixtures of Nafion and GQDs-Cu dispersion at proportions of 1/1 and 1/2 (in volume) were tested. The response, in terms of peak current (I

                           p
                        ) of blank (without creatinine), was more reproducible using Nafion-GQDs-Cu dispersion at 1/1 v/v (Fig. 4B).

Since Cu/Cu2+ oxidation proceeds probably through adsorption, the catalytic surface area of the Au/Nafion-GQDs-Cu electrode is sufficient to allow complexation with creatinine at lower concentrations. At higher concentrations of analyte the modifier amount should be adjusted to allow enough contact area to proceed an effective interaction with the analyte, thus expanding the analytical response range. Therefore, a voltammetric study (SWV) was conducted using electrodes modified with different amounts of the GQDs-Cu, prepared using different proportions of Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.03, 0.06, and 0.09 g) for 0.6 g of citric acid, also keeping the proportion of GQDs-Cu and Nafion constant at 1/1 v/v. It was observed that as the amount of Cu(NO3)2 in the nanocomposite increased the peak current measured in the absence of creatinine (I

                           p0
                        ), using the Au/Nafion-GQDs-Cu electrode, also increased. However, the use of 0.06 g of Cu(NO3)2 was chosen since the higher amount of the copper salt (0.09 g) produce low reproducibility of response.
